ğŸš€ Jenkins and Web Server Deployment on Azure VM
This project demonstrates how to deploy and configure Jenkins and a simple web application on an Ubuntu Azure Virtual Machine, running both services on different ports.

ğŸ§© 1. Project Overview
The goal is to:
Host Jenkins on port 8080
Host a simple HTML web page on port 8081
Verify both services run simultaneously on the same VM
Make them publicly accessible through Azure Network Security Group (NSG)

ğŸ§° 2. Prerequisites
Before starting:
Azure account with permission to create resources
Ubuntu Virtual Machine (minimum 2 GB RAM recommended)
SSH access to VM
Basic understanding of Linux commands

âš™ï¸ 3. Setting up Azure VM
Create an Ubuntu 22.04 LTS VM in Azure.
Allow inbound ports:
22 (SSH)
8080 (Jenkins)
8081 (Web Server)
Connect via SSH:
ssh -i <your-key.pem> azureuser@<vm-public-ip>

ğŸ§± 4. Installing and Configuring Jenkins
Install dependencies
sudo apt update -y
sudo apt install openjdk-17-jdk -y

Add Jenkins repository and install
curl -fsSL https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian/jenkins.io-2023.key | sudo tee \
  /usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc > /dev/null

echo deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc] \
  https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable binary/ | sudo tee \
  /etc/apt/sources.list.d/jenkins.list > /dev/null

sudo apt update -y
sudo apt install jenkins -y

Start and enable Jenkins
sudo systemctl enable jenkins
sudo systemctl start jenkins
sudo systemctl status jenkins

ğŸ”‘ 5. Unlocking Jenkins
Retrieve the initial admin password:
sudo cat /var/lib/jenkins/secrets/initialAdminPassword


Access Jenkins in your browser:
http://<vm-public-ip>:8080
Paste the password, install suggested plugins, and create your admin user.

ğŸŒ 6. Deploying a Simple HTML Web Page
Create and serve a simple HTML file on port 8081.
mkdir ~/simple-web
cd ~/simple-web
nano index.html

Paste:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Hello from Azure VM</title>
</head>
<body style="text-align:center; font-family:Arial;">
  <h1>Welcome to My Simple Web Page ğŸš€</h1>
  <p>Hosted on Ubuntu and running alongside Jenkins.</p>
</body>
</html>

Start a web server:
python3 -m http.server 8081

(Optional) Run in background:
nohup python3 -m http.server 8081 &

ğŸ” 7. Verifying Running Services and Ports
Check active services:
systemctl list-units --type=service --state=running

Check open ports:
sudo ss -tuln

Check which process owns each port:
sudo lsof -i -P -n | grep LISTEN

ğŸŒ 8. Access in Browser
Jenkins â†’ http://<vm-public-ip>:8080
Web App â†’ http://<vm-public-ip>:8081

Make sure Azure NSG allows both ports (8080, 8081).

